<section id="symbols" style="display:none;background:#FAF7F0;padding:4rem 2rem;">
  <div style="max-width:1100px;margin:0 auto;">

    <div style="text-align:center;margin-bottom:2.5rem;">
      <p style="font-size:0.7rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.25em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#C9A84C;margin-bottom:0.5rem;">☘ The Meaning Behind the Piece</p>
      <h2 style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:clamp(1.6rem,3vw,2.2rem);font-weight:900;color:#1B5E20;margin-bottom:1rem;">The Meaning Behind the Piece</h2>
      <p style="font-size:0.9rem;color:#666;max-width:680px;margin:0 auto;line-height:1.8;">Ireland's symbols go back thousands of years — long before they ended up on jewellery in a shop in Kennebunkport. Each one carries a story worth knowing. Here's what they mean, from someone who grew up with them.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Symbol grid -->
    <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(240px,1fr));gap:1.25rem;margin-bottom:3rem;">

      <!-- Celtic Cross -->
      <div style="background:white;border:1.5px solid #e0dbd0;border-top:3px solid #1B5E20;border-radius:3px;padding:1.5rem;">
        <div style="font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:0.75rem;">✝</div>
        <h3 style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1B5E20;margin-bottom:0.4rem;">The Celtic Cross</h3>
        <p style="font-size:0.72rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.12em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#C9A84C;margin-bottom:0.6rem;">A symbol of Irish faith</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:#555;line-height:1.7;">The Celtic cross predates Christianity in Ireland — the circle was there long before the cross was added. When St Patrick arrived, he combined the two, uniting the old faith with the new. You'll still find them standing in churchyards all across Ireland today.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Claddagh -->
      <div style="background:white;border:1.5px solid #e0dbd0;border-top:3px solid #1B5E20;border-radius:3px;padding:1.5rem;">
        <div style="font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:0.75rem;">💍</div>
        <h3 style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1B5E20;margin-bottom:0.4rem;">The Claddagh</h3>
        <p style="font-size:0.72rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.12em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#C9A84C;margin-bottom:0.6rem;">A symbol of love, loyalty & friendship</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:#555;line-height:1.7;">From the fishing village of Claddagh just outside Galway city — my hometown. The hands represent friendship, the heart is love, and the crown is loyalty. How you wear it tells a story: heart pointing out means your heart is free; heart pointing in means it's taken.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Irish Harp -->
      <div style="background:white;border:1.5px solid #e0dbd0;border-top:3px solid #1B5E20;border-radius:3px;padding:1.5rem;">
        <div style="font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:0.75rem;">🎵</div>
        <h3 style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1B5E20;margin-bottom:0.4rem;">The Irish Harp</h3>
        <p style="font-size:0.72rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.12em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#C9A84C;margin-bottom:0.6rem;">A symbol of Irish identity & pride</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:#555;line-height:1.7;">Ireland is the only country in the world with a musical instrument as its national symbol. The harp has appeared on Irish coins, flags and official seals for centuries. Music has always been at the heart of Irish life — it carried the stories when books were scarce.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Shamrock -->
      <div style="background:white;border:1.5px solid #e0dbd0;border-top:3px solid #1B5E20;border-radius:3px;padding:1.5rem;">
        <div style="font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:0.75rem;">☘️</div>
        <h3 style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1B5E20;margin-bottom:0.4rem;">The Shamrock</h3>
        <p style="font-size:0.72rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.12em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#C9A84C;margin-bottom:0.6rem;">A symbol of our emerald isle</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:#555;line-height:1.7;">St Patrick used the three-leafed shamrock to explain the Holy Trinity to the people of Ireland. It stuck. The shamrock became the emblem of the island itself — which is why Ireland is called the Emerald Isle. It really is that green.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Tree of Life -->
      <div style="background:white;border:1.5px solid #e0dbd0;border-top:3px solid #1B5E20;border-radius:3px;padding:1.5rem;">
        <div style="font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:0.75rem;">🌳</div>
        <h3 style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1B5E20;margin-bottom:0.4rem;">The Tree of Life</h3>
        <p style="font-size:0.72rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.12em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#C9A84C;margin-bottom:0.6rem;">A symbol of family & Celtic heritage</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:#555;line-height:1.7;">The ancient Celts believed trees were sacred — doorways between the world of the living and the world beyond. The Tree of Life represents the connection between earth and sky, past and present, and the roots that bind a family together across generations.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Trinity Knot -->
      <div style="background:white;border:1.5px solid #e0dbd0;border-top:3px solid #1B5E20;border-radius:3px;padding:1.5rem;">
        <div style="font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:0.75rem;">🔯</div>
        <h3 style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1B5E20;margin-bottom:0.4rem;">The Trinity Knot</h3>
        <p style="font-size:0.72rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.12em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#C9A84C;margin-bottom:0.6rem;">A symbol of never-ending love & eternal life</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:#555;line-height:1.7;">Three interlocking loops with no beginning and no end. The Celts saw it as the eternal cycle of life, death and rebirth. Early Christians adopted it to represent the Holy Trinity. Today it's one of the most recognisable Celtic symbols in the world — and one of the most meaningful to wear.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- St Bridget's Cross -->
      <div style="background:white;border:1.5px solid #e0dbd0;border-top:3px solid #1B5E20;border-radius:3px;padding:1.5rem;">
        <div style="font-size:2rem;margin-bottom:0.75rem;">✚</div>
        <h3 style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1B5E20;margin-bottom:0.4rem;">St Bridget's Cross</h3>
        <p style="font-size:0.72rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.12em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#C9A84C;margin-bottom:0.6rem;">Ancient Irish symbol of protection</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.82rem;color:#555;line-height:1.7;">Woven from rushes on the 1st of February every year — St Bridget's Day, the first day of spring in the old Irish calendar. A new cross is made and hung above the door to protect the home from fire and illness. You'll still find them in houses all over Ireland today.</p>
      </div>

